														<div id="post-127" class="post-127 post type-post hentry category-uncategorized">
        <div class="posttitle">
          <h2><a href="http://laurenzi.net/?p=127" rel="bookmark" title="Permanent Link to Tufte of the 1860s">Tufte of the 1860s</a></h2>
					<p class="post-info">            
            Jan 3rd, 2011 by <a href="http://laurenzi.net/?author=1" title="Posts by Ian">Ian</a>  </p>          
				</div>

				<div class="entry">
					<p><a href="http://flowingdata.com/2010/12/29/old-map-shows-slavery-in-the-united-states/">This</a> post at <a href="http://flowingdata.com/">flowingdata.com</a> features a graphical representation of the slave populations of the American South that is exceptionally powerful.<br />
<a href="http://laurenzi.net/wp-content/uploads/2011/01/FULLFRAMEmap.jpg"><img src="http://laurenzi.net/wp-content/uploads/2011/01/FULLFRAMEmap-300x246.jpg" alt="" title="Visualizing Slavery" width="300" height="246" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-142" /></a><br />
The post refers to <a href="http://opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/12/09/visualizing-slavery/">this</a>post at the NY Times, which features a gorgeous PDF of the image.</p>
<p>One of the things that strikes me about this figure is it&#8217;s similarity to the map of Napoleon&#8217;s march on Russia by <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles_Joseph_Minard">Joseph Minard</a>, made famous by <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edward_R._Tufte">Ed Tufte</a>&#8216;s books on effective visual communication.<br />
<a href="http://laurenzi.net/wp-content/uploads/2011/01/Minard.jpg"><img src="http://laurenzi.net/wp-content/uploads/2011/01/Minard-300x143.jpg" alt="" title="Minard" width="300" height="143" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-143" /></a></p>
<p>I&#8217;m sure the person who titled the Times piece had the same idea: It&#8217;s called &#8220;Visualizing Slavery&#8221; &#8211; a clear play on the titles of Tufte&#8217;s books.  In any event, Minard&#8217;s figure was in fact made later than the slavery map. Both were propaganda pieces &#8211; Minard&#8217;s is an anti-war piece that doesn&#8217;t even feature Napoleon&#8217;s name. </p>
<p>Was there a &#8220;Renaissance&#8221; of graphical design in the 1860s?  If so, it would seem that the economic driver of graphical design innovation is propaganda!</p>
										<p class="postmetadata"> </p>
				</div>

