        <div class="posttitle">
          <h2><a href="http://laurenzi.net/?p=118" rel="bookmark" title="Permanent Link to Once and for all">Once and for all</a></h2>
					<p class="post-info">            
            Dec 25th, 2010 by <a href="http://laurenzi.net/?author=1" title="Posts by Ian">Ian</a>  </p>          
				</div>

				<div class="entry">
					<p><a href="http://laurenzi.net/wp-content/uploads/2010/12/20101225-115428.jpg"><img src="http://laurenzi.net/wp-content/uploads/2010/12/20101225-115428.jpg" alt="" class="alignnone size-full"/></a></p>
<blockquote><p>God is always faithful to his<br />
promises, but he often surprises us in the way he fulfils them. The<br />
child that was born in Bethlehem did indeed bring liberation, but<br />
not only for the people of that time and place – he was to be the<br />
Saviour of all people <i>throughout the world and throughout<br />
history</i>. And it was not a political liberation that he<br />
brought, achieved through military means: rather, Christ destroyed<br />
death for ever and restored life by means of his shameful death on<br />
the Cross.</p></blockquote>
<p>-Pope Benedict XVI</p>
										<p class="postmetadata"> </p>
