														<div id="post-108" class="post-108 post type-post hentry category-uncategorized tag-education">
        <div class="posttitle">
          <h2><a href="http://laurenzi.net/?p=108" rel="bookmark" title="Permanent Link to The scam">The scam</a></h2>
					<p class="post-info">            
            Dec 10th, 2010 by <a href="http://laurenzi.net/?author=1" title="Posts by Ian">Ian</a>  </p>          
				</div>

				<div class="entry">
					<p>As you ponder why college is costing many people over $50k per year, you may with to add <a href="http://chronicle.com/blogs/innovations/the-great-college-degree-scam/28067">this</a> to your reading. Key quote:<br />
<blockquote>approximately 60 percent of the increase in the number of college graduates from 1992 to 2008 worked in jobs that the BLS considers relatively low skilled—occupations where many participants have only high school diplomas and often even less. Only a minority of the increment in our nation’s stock of college graduates is filling jobs historically considered as requiring a bachelor’s degree or more.</p></blockquote>
<p>(h/t <a href="http://pajamasmedia.com/instapundit/">Instapundit</a></p>
<p>Today, the only reason why college graduates have higher &#8220;on average&#8221; salaries than non grads is because engineers, scientists, doctors, accountants, actuaries, etc. are counted in that average. Remove those specialties and you&#8217;ll find that college is otherwise typically a huge waste of money.</p>
<p>For an estimate of how much your monthly loan payments will be, click <a href="http://www.finaid.org/calculators/loanpayments.phtml">here</a>. Given $200k of debt, (4 years in most private schools) you&#8217;ll have payments of about $2,300 per month which start the month following graduation. Unless you make $60,000 or more per year (which will net you about $3,300 per month), you can&#8217;t afford it. Even at that salary, could you make rent, groceries, utilities etc. with $1,000?</p>
<p>Now ask yourself this question: <i>Will I make this much when I graduate?</i></p>
										<p class="postmetadata">Tags: <a href="http://laurenzi.net/?tag=education" rel="tag">education</a><br/> </p>
